# Phase 9 – Logging, Runtime Configuration, UI/UX & Background Job Enhancements
## Functional Requirements & Acceptance Criteria (Revision 1)

> **Purpose**
>
> This phase focuses on improving observability, logging, runtime diagnostics, user experience, background processing, and application usability. All requirements below are **mandatory** unless explicitly marked otherwise.

---

# 1. Objective

Enhance the application by introducing:

- Enterprise-grade logging
- Runtime log level switching
- Better auditability
- Improved background job experience
- Better cache utilization
- Better Generate Report workflow
- Improved Settings integration
- UI usability improvements
- Fix Version loading improvements

The implementation should follow enterprise Java/Spring Boot best practices.

---

# 2. Functional Requirements

---

# FR-1 Enterprise Logging Framework

Implement consistent logging across the entire application.

Logging shall be available for:

- UI Actions
- REST Controllers
- Services
- Repository Layer
- Scheduled Jobs
- Background Jobs
- External API Calls
- Authentication
- Authorization
- Override Workflow
- Approval Workflow
- Generate Report
- Kubernetes Calls
- GitHub Calls
- iTrack Calls
- Veracode Calls
- Database Updates

---

# FR-2 User Context Logging

Every log entry shall include the authenticated user.

Use MDC (Mapped Diagnostic Context).

Populate MDC with at minimum:

- Username
- User Role
- Session ID (if available)
- Correlation ID
- Request ID

All logs generated during the request lifecycle shall automatically include this information.

---

# FR-3 Logging Standards

Follow Spring Boot / SLF4J logging best practices.

Use log levels appropriately.

### INFO

Business events

Examples:

- User logged in
- Fetch Stories started
- Generate Report started
- Override submitted
- Approval completed
- Background Job started
- Background Job completed

---

### DEBUG

Detailed execution information

Examples:

- API payload summaries
- Query execution details
- Branch comparison details
- Commit analysis
- Kubernetes label parsing
- Cache hit/miss information

Avoid logging sensitive data such as tokens, cookies, passwords, or secrets.

---

### WARN

Recoverable issues

Examples:

- Missing optional configuration
- Retry initiated
- Missing deployment labels

---

### ERROR

Unexpected failures

Include full stack trace where appropriate.

---

# FR-4 Runtime Log Level Control

Introduce runtime log-level configuration.

Only **Admin** users shall have access.

Settings Page

Add:

```
Application Log Level
```

Supported values:

- INFO
- DEBUG

When changed,

new requests shall immediately use the selected log level without requiring an application restart.

If runtime switching cannot safely change framework logger levels, implement an application-level logging toggle for custom debug logs while documenting the limitation.

---

# FR-5 UI Action Logging

Log all significant UI actions.

Examples:

- Team selected
- Fix Version selected
- Fetch Stories
- Fetch Components
- Generate Report
- Review Commits opened
- Override Requested
- Override Approved
- Release Readiness viewed
- Scan History viewed
- Settings updated
- Test Connection executed

Every action shall include:

- Username
- Timestamp
- Team
- Fix Version (where applicable)

---

# FR-6 Comment Length Enhancement

Increase Override Comment capacity.

Target:

Up to 2000 characters.

Minimum acceptable:

1000 characters.

If database limitations exist,

minimum acceptable size:

500 characters.

Update:

- Database column
- Entity validation
- DTO validation
- UI validation

All layers must remain consistent.

---

# FR-7 Long Comment UI

Review the UI behavior for long comments.

Requirements:

- Multi-line text area
- Character counter
- Graceful wrapping
- Responsive layout
- Read More / Read Less (if needed)
- Proper scrolling for lengthy content

The page must remain clean and readable.

---

# FR-8 Loading Message Improvements

During Component loading,

display:

- Team
- Fix Version

Example:

```
Loading components for

Team: OC Platform

Fix Version: 25.14

Please wait...
```

This removes ambiguity for long-running operations.

---

# FR-9 Background Job Continuity

Background jobs shall continue executing independently of UI navigation.

Users shall be able to navigate freely without interrupting running jobs.

Job execution shall not depend on the current browser page.

---

# FR-10 Automatic Cache Usage

Once a background job completes,

all generated data shall be stored in the database.

Subsequent requests shall load data from the database cache instead of re-fetching external systems unless the user explicitly performs a Force Refresh.

This includes:

- Stories
- Components
- Previous Release Metadata
- Kubernetes Metadata
- Configuration Differences
- Deployment Readiness

---

# FR-11 Background Job Completion Message

During long-running operations,

display friendly status messaging.

Example:

```
Your report is being generated.

Feel free to continue using the application.

The results will automatically become available once processing completes.
```

Avoid blocking the UI.

Do not freeze the browser.

---

# FR-12 Fix Version Loading

Review the Fix Version implementation.

Requirements:

- Load Fix Versions directly from the database.
- Eliminate duplicate entries.
- Do not derive or calculate release identifiers.
- Respect the existing data model.
- Use only the persisted Fix Version values.

---

# FR-13 Fix Version Metadata

Review Fix Version fields.

Current understanding:

- From Date
- To Date

Validate the existing implementation.

Do not introduce unnecessary calculated dates.

If an additional date exists, verify whether it is required.

Remove or ignore it if it serves no business purpose.

---

# FR-14 Generate Report Validation

The Generate Report page shall include a lightweight **Validate Connections** action.

Purpose:

Allow users to verify required external connections without navigating to Settings.

This action shall test only the minimum required connections.

Mandatory:

- GitHub
- iTrack
- Production East OR Production West Kubernetes

Display pass/fail status for each dependency.

This validation shall not modify stored credentials.

---

# FR-15 Settings Ownership

Credentials shall only be entered and modified in the Settings page.

Remove credential input fields from other pages.

Other pages may:

- Display connection status
- Trigger connection validation

They must not allow credential editing.

---

# FR-16 Connection Validation

Any page requiring external integrations may include a **Test Connection** action.

This action shall:

- Use credentials already stored in Settings
- Perform validation
- Update connection status indicators
- Never request credentials again

---

# FR-17 Background Job UX

All long-running operations shall be asynchronous.

Provide:

- Job ID
- Current Status
- Started Time
- Last Updated Time
- Completion Time (when available)

Users shall be able to monitor progress through Scan History or Job History.

---

# FR-18 Logging for Background Jobs

Every background job shall log:

- Job ID
- User
- Team
- Fix Version
- Start Time
- End Time
- Duration
- Success/Failure
- External systems accessed
- Number of records processed

---

# FR-19 Cache Logging

Log cache behavior.

Examples:

- Cache Hit
- Cache Miss
- Cache Refresh
- Force Refresh
- Database Reload

These logs should primarily be DEBUG level.

---

# FR-20 Security

Never log:

- GitHub Tokens
- iTrack Tokens
- Kubernetes Cookies
- Veracode Keys
- Passwords
- Authorization Headers
- Session Secrets

Sensitive values must always be masked or omitted.

---

# 3. Non-Functional Requirements

- Follow SLF4J logging best practices.
- Keep log messages structured and meaningful.
- Avoid duplicate logging.
- Ensure asynchronous jobs are resilient.
- Preserve existing functionality.
- Avoid UI blocking.
- Maintain backward compatibility.
- Use reusable helper classes where appropriate.

---

# 4. Acceptance Criteria

### AC-1
Enterprise logging shall be implemented consistently across UI, backend, services, repositories, and background jobs.

### AC-2
Every log entry shall include user context using MDC (Username, Role, Correlation ID, etc.).

### AC-3
Logging levels shall follow INFO, DEBUG, WARN, and ERROR best practices.

### AC-4
Only Admin users shall be able to change the runtime log level.

### AC-5
Runtime log level changes shall take effect without restarting the application where technically feasible.

### AC-6
All major UI actions shall be logged with sufficient business context.

### AC-7
Override comments shall support at least 1000 characters (preferably up to 2000), with all application layers updated accordingly.

### AC-8
The UI shall remain clean and readable when displaying lengthy comments.

### AC-9
Component loading messages shall display both Team and Fix Version.

### AC-10
Background jobs shall continue running even if users navigate away from the current page.

### AC-11
Completed job results shall be persisted and reused from the database cache.

### AC-12
Long-running operations shall never block or freeze the UI.

### AC-13
Friendly progress messages shall be displayed while background jobs are executing.

### AC-14
Fix Version values shall be loaded directly from the database without duplicates or unnecessary calculations.

### AC-15
Only valid Fix Version metadata shall be displayed.

### AC-16
Generate Report shall include a lightweight **Validate Connections** action for required integrations.

### AC-17
Credential management shall remain exclusive to the Settings page.

### AC-18
Other pages may validate connections but shall never allow credential editing.

### AC-19
Background jobs shall expose Job ID, execution status, timestamps, and processing metrics.

### AC-20
Background job execution shall be fully logged.

### AC-21
Cache usage (hits, misses, refreshes) shall be logged at DEBUG level.

### AC-22
No sensitive credentials, cookies, or secrets shall ever be written to application logs.

### AC-23
All enhancements shall remain backward compatible with the existing implementation.

---

# Implementation Notes

- Reuse existing services wherever possible.
- Avoid duplicate implementations.
- Prefer configuration-driven behavior.
- Keep logging structured, searchable, and suitable for production support.
- Validate all UI changes with long-running operations and large datasets.
- Consider future integration with centralized logging platforms (e.g., ELK/OpenSearch, Splunk, Azure Monitor) by using consistent log formats and correlation IDs.
- The implementation is complete only when all Functional Requirements (FR) and Acceptance Criteria (AC) in this document have been satisfied.
